Angioedema, vomiting, flushing, rhinorrhea, and wheezing are symptoms of a severe allergic reaction. Seek immediate medical attention.
Angioedema, vomiting, flushing, rhinorrhea, and wheezing may also be symptoms of a respiratory infection. If you are experiencing these symptoms, see a doctor to get a diagnosis and treatment plan.

1. Gastroenteritis: This is the most likely diagnosis, as it encompasses all the symptoms you described. It is an inflammation of the stomach and intestines, usually caused by a viral or bacterial infection. Symptoms include abdominal cramps, vomiting, diarrhea, and sometimes nausea, fever, and headache.

2. Food poisoning: This is another possibility, especially if the symptoms started shortly after eating contaminated food. Symptoms are similar to gastroenteritis, but may also include sweating, chills, and muscle aches.

3. Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS): This is a chronic condition that can cause abdominal pain, bloating, diarrhea, and constipation. It is not usually accompanied by vomiting or wheezing, but it is possible.

4. Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD): This is a group of chronic inflammatory disorders of the digestive tract, including Crohns disease and ulcerative colitis. Symptoms can include abdominal pain, diarrhea, weight loss, and fatigue. In some cases, IBD can also cause wheezing and dyspnea.

5. Asthma: This is a chronic respiratory disease that can cause wheezing, coughing, and shortness of breath. It is sometimes triggered by viral infections, which can also cause abdominal cramps, vomiting, and diarrhea.

6. Pneumonia: This is an infection of the lungs that can cause fever, cough, shortness of breath, and chest pain. In some cases, it can also cause abdominal pain, vomiting, and diarrhea.

7. Bronchitis: This is an inflammation of the bronchi, the airways that carry air to and from the lungs. Symptoms include coughing, wheezing, and shortness of breath. It can sometimes be accompanied by abdominal pain, vomiting, and diarrhea.

8. Cystic fibrosis: This is a genetic disorder that affects the lungs and digestive system. Symptoms include wheezing, coughing, shortness of breath, and frequent lung infections. It can also cause abdominal pain, vomiting, and diarrhea.

9. Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD): This is a condition where stomach acid flows back up into the esophagus, causing heartburn and regurgitation. It can sometimes cause abdominal pain, vomiting, and diarrhea.

10. Anxiety: Anxiety can sometimes cause physical symptoms such as abdominal pain, vomiting, diarrhea, wheezing, and shortness of breath.

Stroke: Sudden weakness, numbness, or paralysis on one side of the body, especially the face, arm, or leg. May also include problems with vision, speech, and balance.
Transient ischemic attack (TIA): Similar symptoms to a stroke, but the symptoms typically last less than an hour and dont result in permanent damage. Often referred to as a mini-stroke.
Brain tumor: A mass of abnormal cells in the brain that can cause a variety of symptoms, including headaches, seizures, and neurological deficits such as weakness or numbness.

Multiple sclerosis (MS): A chronic disease that affects the central nervous system, causing inflammation and damage to the myelin sheath, which protects nerve fibers. This can lead to a variety of symptoms, including numbness, weakness, and vision problems.
Meningitis: An inflammation of the membranes that surround the brain and spinal cord, usually caused by an infection. Symptoms can include headache, fever, stiff neck, and sensitivity to light.
Encephalitis: An inflammation of the brain, usually caused by an infection. Symptoms can include headache, fever, confusion, and seizures.

Guillain-Barre syndrome: A rare autoimmune disorder that affects the peripheral nerves, causing weakness, numbness, and tingling. Symptoms typically start in the feet and legs and spread upward to the arms and face.
Cervical radiculopathy: A condition that occurs when a nerve root in the neck is compressed, causing pain, numbness, and weakness in the arm or shoulder.
Fibromyalgia: A chronic pain disorder that affects the muscles and soft tissues. Symptoms can include widespread pain, fatigue, sleep problems, and cognitive difficulties.

Lyme disease: A bacterial infection that can cause a variety of symptoms, including fever, headache, fatigue, and a characteristic bulls-eye rash. In some cases, it can also affect the nervous system, causing numbness, weakness, and paralysis.
